Here’s a concise SQL + policy draft you can run in Supabase:
Schema:
- profiles:
  create table profiles (
    user_id uuid primary key references auth.users(id) on delete cascade,
    email text unique,
    full_name text,
    avatar_url text,
    created_at timestamp with time zone default now()
  );
- projects:
  create table projects (
    id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
    owner_id uuid references auth.users(id) on delete cascade,
    title text not null,
    description text,
    created_at timestamp with time zone default now()
  );
- tasks:
  create table tasks (
    id uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
    project_id uuid references projects(id) on delete cascade,
    owner_id uuid references auth.users(id) on delete cascade,
    title text not null,
    status text check (status in ('todo','in_progress','done')) default 'todo',
    due_date date,
    created_at timestamp with time zone default now()
  );
Enable RLS:
- alter table profiles enable row level security;
- alter table projects enable row level security;
- alter table tasks enable row level security;
Policies:
- profiles (owner-only):
  create policy "read own profile" on profiles for select using (user_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "insert own profile" on profiles for insert with check (user_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "update own profile" on profiles for update using (user_id = auth.uid());
- projects (owner-only):
  create policy "read own projects" on projects for select using (owner_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "insert own projects" on projects for insert with check (owner_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "update own projects" on projects for update using (owner_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "delete own projects" on projects for delete using (owner_id = auth.uid());
- tasks (owner-only; optionally also ensure task’s project belongs to same owner):
  create policy "read own tasks" on tasks for select using (owner_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "insert own tasks" on tasks for insert with check (owner_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "update own tasks" on tasks for update using (owner_id = auth.uid());
  create policy "delete own tasks" on tasks for delete using (owner_id = auth.uid());
Optional stricter task policy:
- add a constraint ensuring tasks.owner_id = (select owner_id from projects where projects.id = tasks.project_id);
Auth wiring checklist (Next.js 14 App Router):
- Install: npm i @supabase/supabase-js @supabase/auth-helpers-nextjs.
- Env: add SUPABASE_URL and SUPABASE_ANON_KEY to .env.local; restart dev server.
- Client utilities: create a browser client (createClient) and a server client using the auth helpers for reading sessions in server components/actions.
- Middleware or route protection: add logic to redirect unauthenticated users away from /dashboard and other protected routes.
- Auth pages: build /signin with magic link form; on success redirect to /dashboard.
- Profile bootstrap: after first login, upsert profiles row with user_id and email.
- Data access: use the user session’s access token; all reads/writes occur under RLS automatically.
- Testing: verify anon cannot read/write; authenticated user can only see their own rows.
Reminders and budget:
- I’ll nudge you to check Dune 2 tickets at 8 pm; consider discount Tuesday or matinee to protect the $800 savings target.
- Today’s task added: email Sarah about the FocusFlow logo (mention your Spotify connection and timeline).
- Smoothie budget tip: frozen spinach, banana, peanut butter, oats, and tap water or cheap almond milk — all under $2 per serving. Keeps the detox vibe without the Whole Foods price tag.
Want me to generate a quick seed script for a demo project and task tied to your user after first sign-in?

Here’s a concise, budget-friendly prompt template you can use. Pass it the structured fields we discussed.

Instruction:
“You are a summarization assistant. Produce a brief, factual summary and concrete action items strictly from the provided session context. Do not invent details, tasks, or metrics. If information is missing, say so briefly.”

Context (variables to fill):
- Session title: {session_title}
- Goal: {session_goal}
- Duration: {start_timestamp} to {end_timestamp}
- Notes: {user_notes}
- Tasks touched: {tasks_touched}
- Blockers: {blockers}
- Tags: {context_tags}

Output format:
- Summary: 1–2 sentences, max 40–60 words.
- Action items: 3–5 bullets, each ≤15 words, all start with a verb.
- Optional tags: concise list from context, if present.

Style rules:
- Be concise and specific.
- No speculation or new ideas not present in context.
- If context is empty: “Insufficient context to summarize.”

This keeps outputs tight, predictable, and cheap. You can further cap response length via your API call parameters. Also, remember: buy milk.
